  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Somalia Livelihood Support Project (SOLIS)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">1) 5 groups of women trained on kitchen gardening

2) 3 Maternal and Child Health centers (MCH) receive demonstration gardens

3) Rehabilitate 28 waterpoints

4) Train 28 water user committees

5) Run 28 hygiene promotion campaigns</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Internally displaced persons (IDPs), Women&apos;s groups</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Horn of Africa region is facing a protracted drought situation, with millions of livelihoods threatened and lives at risk. At the center of this humanitarian crisis, more than 2 million Somalis are in need of emergency livelihood and lifesaving assistance. The proposed 12 month intervention is a continuation of World Concern Development Organization (WCDO) activities in Northwest Somalia (Somaliland), focusing on water supply, hygiene training and vegetable gardening in two regions, Togdheer and Sanaag. These two pastoralist regions have been severely affected by poor and delayed rain over several seasons, and lack of water supply has affected livelihoods, nutrition and health throughout the population. WCDO plans to rehabilitate and improve 28 community water sources (berkads and shallow wells), upgrade water catchment at four schools and four health facilities, and initiate 8 trial gardens among women&#x2019;s groups and alongside health facilities. In addition, promotion of hygiene, nutrition and sanitation messages will be conducted together with distributions of soap.</narrative>
  </description>
